{"query": "What are the documented benefits and harms of amending soil with additives like organic matter, lime, or fertilizer after planting trees?", "summary": "Based on the action documents reviewed, soil amendments after tree planting show mixed results depending on the type of amendment and tree species. Organic matter amendments demonstrate several benefits including increased microbial biomass and activity (902), higher soil organic carbon levels (902), and increased soil nutrients (902). However, in wetland environments, high amounts of compost can negatively impact plant community composition by favoring species characteristic of drier conditions and reducing plant species richness and diversity (3310), though it can increase individual tree size (3310). Manure applications show mixed effects on tree survival and growth depending on species and dose (3311).

Lime applications reveal predominantly negative or neutral effects. Studies found lime application decreased pine seedling survival (1259), typically reduced survival of planted fen herbs (1825), and reduced growth rates for most peat swamp tree seedlings (1825). However, some studies found lime increased survival of planted fen mosses (1825) and vegetation cover in one study (1249).

Fertilizer applications show variable results. Some studies found fertilizer increased tree size (1260, 3306) and growth rates (3306), while others found no significant effects on tree height, diameter, survival, or health (1260, 3306). One study reported mixed effects on seedling survival and height (1260).", "action_ids": ["902", "3310", "3311", "1259", "1825", "1249", "1260", "3306"]}

